{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:19:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:19:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15943"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15943"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.1,0.17,0.47,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8634"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8634"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58315"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8702"},{"type":"tags","id":"8703"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pituitary gland is a crucial endocrine organ that develops from two distinct embryological sources. The anterior portion forms from an upward growth called Rathke\u0027s pouch, while the posterior portion develops as a downward extension of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the anterior pituitary gland?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mesoderm","Neural crest cells","Endoderm","Oral ectoderm","Neural ectoderm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) develops from \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral ectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E through the formation of Rathke\u0027s pouch, which is an upward invagination of the primitive oral cavity roof.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis) develops from \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural ectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E as a downward growth (infundibulum) from the diencephalon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E does not contribute to pituitary formation, though it forms nearby structures like blood vessels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to many head and neck structures but not the pituitary gland\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the gastrointestinal tract lining but not the pituitary\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis embryological origin explains why the anterior pituitary contains hormone-secreting endocrine cells while the posterior pituitary contains nerve terminals that release neurohormones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior pituitary gland (adenohypophysis) develops from Rathke\u0027s pouch, an upward extension of oral ectoderm.","The posterior pituitary gland (neurohypophysis) develops from neural ectoderm as a downward extension of the diencephalon.","Understanding embryological origins helps explain the distinct functions of the anterior and posterior pituitary."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Scott IS, Chattopadhyay A, Ansorge O. Development and Microscopic Anatomy of the Pituitary Gland. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com. [Updated 2024 Sep 28]. Available at:  https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK425703/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15943"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:56:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T09:58:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8634"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72845"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30"